The following project focus on the analysis of a dataset of Bank Marketing which contains data or information about customers and aims to get useful insights from the data and predict if a new customer will accept a deposit offer or not. ¶

**Dataset contains Total 17 columns/Features:**
¶

Bank Client Data
¶

1 - age : Age of customer(numeric)¶

2 - job : Job Type (categorical: 'admin.','blue-collar','entrepreneur','housemaid','management','retired','self-employed','services','student','technician','unemployed','unknown')¶

3 - marital : marital status (categorical: 'divorced','married','single','unknown')¶

4 - education (categorical: 'primary','secondary','tertiary','unknown')¶

5 - default: has credit in default? (categorical: yes/no)¶

6 - balance: bank balance(RS)¶

7 - housing: has housing loan? (categorical: yes/no)¶

8 - loan: has personal loan? (categorical: yes/no)¶

Info related with the last contact of the current campaign:
¶

9 - contact: contact communication type (categorical: 'cellular','telephone','unknown')¶

10 - month: last contact month of year (categorical: 'jan', 'feb', 'mar', ..., 'nov', 'dec')¶

11 - day: last contact day of the week (categorical: '1','2','3',....,'29','30','31')¶

12 - duration: last contact duration, in seconds (numeric).¶

Other Attributes:
¶

13 - campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (numeric, includes last contact)¶

14 - pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (numeric)¶

15 - previous: number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client (numeric)¶

16 - poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign (categorical: 'failure','nonexistent','success')¶

Output variable (desired target):
¶

17 - y - has the client subscribed a term deposit? (binary: yes/no)¶

Dealing with Outliers

We remove outliers from the numeric features that are balance, duration, pdays, campaign and previous¶

We remove all those values from data set which are 3 standard deviation above or below the mean¶

In [183]:
sns.heatmap(new_df[['age', 'balance', 'day', 'duration', 'campaign', 'previous','pdays']].corr(),cmap="Blues")
Out[183]:
<AxesSubplot:>

Above is correlation plot which shows which of the numeric features are correlated with each other. We know that when features are correlated with each other then we have Multi-colinearity Problem. Here the variables previous and pdays are highly correlated with each other. It may be because pdays -1 means peoples are new or involving 1st time in campaign and they have no previous contact so previous ==0. Now as the pdays and previous columns have 80% values as -1 and 0 respectively therefore they are highly correlated with each other.¶

Therefore, we drop the column pdays from our dataset.¶

In [47]:
new_df.drop("pdays",inplace=True,axis=1)
